I ordered mutter paneer for delivery.  It was DELICIOUS.  Very well made.  A few things...after reading other reviews I knew not to expect utensils so planned ahead.  Sure enough, no plates, utensils or napkins.    Some of the complaints said there was too little food, but my containers were full to the brim and I felt overfull and sleepy at the end of my lunch so I'd say they give a generous portion.  However, I did NOT order from the lunch menu as my item wasn't one of the choices.  The menu didn't tell you that you get a whole naan with entrees, so I ordered an extra naan off the menu.  I had two HUGE naan breads to deal with (I could have saved $3). An entree,  sweet lassi, extra naan and $5 tip, my lunch cost $29.  That's a bit high for the area, but I feel like I got my money's worth.

He immediately went into defense mode saying that the chef wears a net, well clearly the net wasn't completely effective that day. I told them I just wanted a clean plate, there was no protocol for them seemingly for situations like this as all he could do was be defensive. Then it was sort of just a "okay, yeah, we'll redo it attitude." Even though I clearly said just bring me a different plate. Anyhow, the dish came again. There was never an apology, not from this server or the one who took our check. It was ridiculous. As great as the food was, I am more than likely not going to go there again.

Went there with my friends.Out of everything Chicken Tikka Masala kind of satisfied us. According to the online menu, I asked the person who was handling the register “May I please have the menu?” He said “That’s the menu on of the wall and all the food right front of you?” Me- I was shocked but anyway we ordered from what he showed us. It was a big disappointment for all of us. Because according to the review from the people, they had some good foods we wanted to try out. However, It wasn’t like what we expected. Also, the place is really unorganized and needs a strong management to keep the store clean and organized. When we entered the restaurant it was a mess like all wind from outside went inside of the restaurant and that wasn’t welcoming at all lol. Even tho we went in to try out anyway. So we ordered what the person showed us. It was like a combo- for example, Two entree’s with rice and nan. the we had are -  1) Vindaloo Chiken, I believe. 2) Chicken Curry. 3) Chicken Tikka Masala.  The rice was good. The Nan please that was embarrassing. What was the chef thinking? Who makes nan like that? rubbery tastes bland flat as a roti. It totally pissed me off. Okay moving on to next-  First- Chicken curry what can I say. The curry was was good honestly but the chicken comon it’s too DRY!!!!! Why u do this?  Next- Vindaloo Chicken It was ruined. Over spiced with clove and other spices. Could have been better.  lastly- Chicken Tikka Masala. Now that was good ! but lacks a little salt/flavor. Could be better. But man the chicken mad dry.  If the chicken is overcooked it comes dry because it doesn’t have any fat.  This place can be way better if everybody cares what they doing specially the food. The kitchen needs focus more on what and how they cooking. The ingredients needs The service needs to be better.  Based on other “Good” reviews, what I have experienced is nothing compared to what I read.  Will visit next time if the restaurant makes improvement. Until then I am off. This restaurant has good potential if everyone cares. Specially the Engine room of the restaurant.

So tonight's meal @ Curry Heights started out with me not receiving any water even as the delicious Vege samosa was served.  As I watched the two gentlemen next to me be served water, I was like maybe this is just an oversight.  When my Chicken Vindaloo, Navaratan Korma, and Garlic Naan (which were fantastic!!) arrived, I asked for water.  I was given water  (refilled throughout meal), but no  apology was offerred.  So I'm thinking to myseld, "Don't trip, maybe its just cultural."  I continue to enjoy my meal and after I am done, the waiter asks me to pay in cash because the machine was down for a half hour.  They said I could even pay less.  I said hmmm ok and complete my transaction in cash.  However, I observe the same two gentlemen, who happened to be white, have their cards taken without question.  After their transaction, I ask the two gentlemen if the servers had requested that they pay in cash and they tell me no.  So I wait until the two gentlemen leave and summon the waiter over and ask if there is a reason why the two gentlemen were allowed to pay with card while I was told the machine was down for a half hour.  The waiter told me that Im making a big deal out of nothing and that they would have take my card.  So I stated but you said the machine had been down. That's when he proceeded to wag his finger in my face and speak to me like I am his child.  I stood up and responded why are you pointing your finger at me when you are the one giving preferential treatment to other people.  My review of this establishment is terrible service at best.....racist at worst

When they first opened the chef they had made the sauces from scratch and it was unbelievably good. They have since turned into an ordinary but OK Indian restaurant, but the only real choice in the heights. 4 Stars for the mulligatawny soup and okra Bindi Masala.

The decor is typical of your favorite Indian dining experience - rug, bland wallpaper and a full-on tablecloth, place settings and servile wait-staff - but, the flavor is beyond the typical. The chutneys have an extra punch of sweetness, and the vindaloo is potent without being overpowering with heat. A better reviewer could analyze the taste, but from a lay Indian restaurateur, their kitchen has that umff that makes them stand apart. Mind you, it just opened and serves neither beer or wine. Just go for the grub. You won't be disappointed.
